Q1

What is the relationship between a games Rating and its Global_Sales?

#we define the Sales over 20 milion as outlier 
filtered_data <- final_data %>% filter(Global_Sales <= 2000)

# Build a linear model using the filtered data
model <- lm(Global_Sales ~ Rating, data = filtered_data)
# Print the summary of the model
summary(model)

Q2

Based on past sales data and trends, predict which Genre of game is likely to have the highest Global_Sales in the next year

# Filter only rows with valid Year and Global_Sales
filtered_data <- fir_dataset %>%
  filter(!is.na(Year), !is.na(Global_Sales))

# Group by Year and Genre and sum the Global_Sales
grouped_data <- filtered_data %>%
  group_by(Year, Genre) %>%
  summarise(Total_Global_Sales = sum(Global_Sales), .groups = "drop")

# Split the data by Genre
split_data <- split(grouped_data, grouped_data$Genre)

# Function to forecast sales
forecast_sales <- function(data) {
  model <- auto.arima(data$Total_Global_Sales, seasonal = TRUE)
  forecast(model, h=1)$mean
}

# Apply the function to each Genre
forecasts <- lapply(split_data, forecast_sales)

# Extract the genre with the highest forecasted sales
predicted_genre <- names(which.max(unlist(forecasts)))

print(predicted_genre)
## [1] "Action"

Q3

What platform has the highest average Global Sales, and which one has the lowest? And plot a histogram for all platforms

# Group by Platform and calculate the average Global Sales
platform_sales <- fir_dataset %>%
  group_by(Platform) %>%
  summarise(Avg_Global_Sales = mean(Global_Sales, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(Avg_Global_Sales)

# Display which platform has the highest and lowest average Global Sales
highest_platform <- tail(platform_sales, 1)
lowest_platform <- head(platform_sales, 1)

print(highest_platform)
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   Platform Avg_Global_Sales
##   <chr>               <dbl>
## 1 GB                   2.61
print(lowest_platform)
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   Platform Avg_Global_Sales
##   <chr>               <dbl>
## 1 PCFX                 0.03
# Plot a histogram for all platforms
ggplot(platform_sales, aes(x = reorder(Platform, -Avg_Global_Sales), y = Avg_Global_Sales)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Average Global Sales by Platform",
       x = "Platform",
       y = "Average Global Sales") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Q4

We can roughly categorize gaming platforms into 4 Sony Nintendo Microsoft Others What are the sales of each of these four

library(tidyverse)


platform_categories <- list(
  Sony = c("PS4", "PS3", "PS2", "PSP", "PSV"),
  Microsoft = c("X360", "XOne", "XB"),
  Nintendo = c("GB", "NES", "SNES", "Wii", "N64", "WiiU", "3DS", "GBA", "DS", "GC"),
  Others = c("GEN", "2600", "DC", "PC", "WS", "SAT", "TG16", "NG", "GG", "3DO", "PCFX")
)


final_data$Platform_Category <- case_when(
  final_data$Platform %in% platform_categories$Sony ~ "Sony",
  final_data$Platform %in% platform_categories$Microsoft ~ "Microsoft",
  final_data$Platform %in% platform_categories$Nintendo ~ "Nintendo",
  TRUE ~ "Others"
)
final_data$Platform_Category <- case_when(
  final_data$Platform %in% platform_categories$Sony ~ "Sony",
  final_data$Platform %in% platform_categories$Microsoft ~ "Microsoft",
  final_data$Platform %in% platform_categories$Nintendo ~ "Nintendo",
  TRUE ~ "Others"
)

average_sales_df <- final_data %>%
  group_by(Platform_Category) %>%
  summarise(Average_Global_Sales = sum(Global_Sales, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(desc(Average_Global_Sales))

ggplot(average_sales_df, aes(x = reorder(Platform_Category, -Average_Global_Sales), y = Average_Global_Sales)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Average Global Sales by Platform Category",
       x = "Platform Category",
       y = "Average Global Sales") +
  theme_minimal()

Q5

Do the regions have their own favorite genres and types of consoles?

popular_genre_by_region <- fir_dataset %>%
  group_by(Genre) %>%
  summarise(
    NA_Sales = sum(NA_Sales, na.rm = TRUE),
    EU_Sales = sum(EU_Sales, na.rm = TRUE),
    JP_Sales = sum(JP_Sales, na.rm = TRUE),
    Other_Sales = sum(Other_Sales, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  gather(Region, Sales, -Genre) %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  top_n(1, Sales) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(Region, Genre)


popular_genre_by_region %>% print()

Q6

Do the four manufacturers specialize in the types of games they release (judged by the total number of types of games released by the manufacturer) and also output the types of games that sell the most in the top 10 games for each plate

selected_publishers <- c("Nintendo", "Microsoft",  "Sony")


popular_genre_by_publisher <- final_data %>%
  filter(Platform_Category %in% selected_publishers) %>%
  group_by(Platform_Category, Genre) %>%
  summarise(Count = n()) %>%
  arrange(Platform_Category, desc(Count)) %>%
  group_by(Platform_Category) %>%
  slice_head(n = 1) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Platform_Category'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
popular_genre_by_publisher %>% print()
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   Platform_Category Genre  Count
##   <chr>             <chr>  <int>
## 1 Microsoft         Action    72
## 2 Nintendo          Action    72
## 3 Sony              Action   116
top_10_games_by_platform <- final_data %>%
  group_by(Platform_Category) %>%
  top_n(10, Global_Sales) %>%
  ungroup()


popular_genre_in_top_10_by_platform <- top_10_games_by_platform %>%
  filter(Platform_Category %in% selected_publishers) %>%
  group_by(Platform_Category, Genre) %>%
  summarise(Count = n()) %>%
  arrange(Platform_Category, desc(Count)) %>%
  group_by(Platform_Category) %>%
  slice_head(n = 1) %>%

 Q2data <- final_data %>%
  mutate(Year = if_else(Year == "N/A", NA_character_, Year)) %>% 
  mutate(Year = if_else(grepl("^\\d+$", Year), as.numeric(Year), NA_real_))%>% 
  na.omit(final_data) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(Sequel = ifelse(str_detect(Name, "[:0-9IXV]"), 1, 0))%>%
  mutate(NoR = ifelse(grepl("K", NoR), 
                      as.numeric(sub("K", "", NoR)) * 1000, 
                      as.numeric(NoR)))%>%
  mutate(Plays = ifelse(grepl("K", NoR), 
                      as.numeric(sub("K", "", NoR)) * 1000, 
                      as.numeric(NoR)))

Q4

Q4data <- Q2data%>%
  mutate(High_Rating = ifelse(Rating >= 4, 1, 0))
set.seed(123) 
sample_index <- sample(seq_len(nrow(Q4data)), size = 0.7*nrow(Q4data)) 
train_data2 <- Q4data[sample_index, ]
test_data2 <- Q4data[-sample_index, ]
model_logistic <- glm(High_Rating ~ Year + NoR + Genre + Platform_Category + Sequel + Global_Sales, family = binomial(link='logit'), data = train_data2)


model_tree <- rpart(High_Rating ~ Year + NoR + Genre + Platform_Category + Sequel + Global_Sales, data = train_data2, method = "class")


model_svm <- svm(High_Rating ~ Year + NoR + Genre + Platform_Category + Sequel + Global_Sales, data = train_data2, kernel = "radial", cost = 10, gamma = 0.1)
pred_logistic <- predict(model_logistic, newdata = test_data2, type = "response")

pred_logistic_class <- ifelse(pred_logistic > 0.5, 1, 0)

actual_labels <- test_data2$High_Rating  
accuracy <- sum(pred_logistic_class == actual_labels) / length(actual_labels)
print(paste("accuracy for logistic:", round(accuracy, 4)))
## [1] "accuracy for logistic: 0.8256"
confusion_matrix_logistic <- table(Actual = actual_labels, Predicted = pred_logistic_class)

df_melted_logistic <- melt(as.data.frame(confusion_matrix_logistic))
## Using Actual, Predicted as id variables
ggplot(data = df_melted_logistic, aes(x = Predicted, y = Actual )) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = value), color = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf("%d", value)), vjust = 1) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "blue") +
  theme_minimal() +
 labs(title="Decision Tree Confusion Matrix Heatmap", x="Predicted", y="Actual", fill="Count")

pred_tree <- predict(model_tree, newdata = test_data2, type = "class")

actual_labels_tree <- test_data2$High_Rating  
accuracy_tree <- sum(pred_tree == actual_labels_tree) / length(actual_labels_tree)
print(paste("accuracy for decision tree:", round(accuracy_tree, 4)))
## [1] "accuracy for decision tree: 0.8434"
conf_matrix_tree <- table(pred_tree, actual_labels_tree)


conf_matrix_melted_tree <- melt(as.matrix(conf_matrix_tree))

ggplot(data = conf_matrix_melted_tree, aes(x=pred_tree, y=actual_labels_tree)) + 
  geom_tile(aes(fill=value), color='white') +
  geom_text(aes(label=sprintf("%d", value)), vjust=1) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low="white", high="blue") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title="Decision Tree Confusion Matrix Heatmap", x="Predicted", y="Actual", fill="Count")

pred_svm <- predict(model_svm, newdata = test_data2)
pred_svm_class <- ifelse(pred_svm > 0.5, 1, 0)
actual_labels_svm <- test_data2$High_Rating
accuracy_svm <- sum(pred_svm_class == actual_labels_svm) / length(actual_labels_svm)
print(paste("accuracy for SVM :", round(accuracy_svm, 4)))
## [1] "accuracy for SVM : 0.8577"
confusion_matrix_svm <- table(Actual = actual_labels_svm, Predicted = pred_svm_class)

df_melted_svm <- melt(as.data.frame(confusion_matrix_svm))
## Using Actual, Predicted as id variables

Summary

PARAGRAPH 1

A preliminary investigation of the data allows us to draw several conclusions and observations:There appears to be a correlation between game ratings (Rating) and global sales (Global_Sales). However, high ratings do not necessarily equate to outstanding sales.Action games tend to have higher global sales in the dataset. When categorizing consoles into mainstream companies such as Sony, Microsoft, and Nintendo, it is clear that Nintendo has a clear advantage in game releases.Different regions show different preferences in terms of gaming platforms and game genres, as shown in Question 5.Different game developers seem to have their own specialized game genres as shown in Q6.Surprisingly, some games received high ratings but did not sell as well. Additionally, while the U.S. market was significant in terms of sales, the gap between Nintendo and Sony in Q4 wasnt as large as expected, considering Nintendos clear dominance in Q3.This leads to a couple of intriguing questions:Can we predict the sales of different game genres from the big three in different regions (e.g.Q5 and Q6)?What are the factors that influence game sales? As highlighted in Q1 and Q2, what is the proportionate impact of each of these factors?How has Nintendos sales trajectory as mentioned in Q3 and Q4 shaped up and how can we predict its sales over the next five years?Based on the extrapolations in Q1 and Q2, can we determine if a game is more likely to receive a higher rating based on certain information?

PARAGRAPH 2

To answer the follow-up question, we used three multiple linear regression and neural network techniques to estimate future sales. Our findings suggest that North American sales do play a pivotal role in influencing global game sales. However, the difference between the predictions of North American and European sales is not as large as expected. In addition, to address the interrelationships between certain variables, we used a covariance matrix. It helped us to find that variables such as Plays and NoR are perfectly linearly correlated (Cor=1). The second problem aimed at predicting whether a game would receive a high rating or not, and we used a variety of methods such as SVM and decision trees. The performance of these models was remarkably similar, with all of them appearing to predict low ratings for games that actually had high ratings. One potential reason for this is that there is a subset of games in our dataset that, despite their high ratings, perform poorly in terms of sales. These questions and their answers are critical for both game developers and gamers. Game companies often aim to get the highest return on investment when strategizing for the next version of a game. This may influence their decisions, such as whether to innovate with new game concepts or continue with a sequel. On the other hand, gamers usually decide whether to buy a game based on past sales figures, game ratings and game genres. These decisions have a direct impact on the games sales trajectory and overall ratings. Therefore, understanding these dynamics is crucial to determine the future direction of the gaming industry.
